---

<Base
  title="Genome browser integration — JBrowseMSA"
  description="Use react-msaview inside JBrowse 2 — an MSA viewer with a tree beside genome annotation, DNA-alignment tracks, and protein↔genome coordinate sync, driven entirely by declarative URLs."
  wide
>
  <article class="prose">
    <h1>In the genome browser</h1>
    <p>
      react-msaview ships as a JBrowse 2 plugin
      (<a href="https://github.com/GMOD/jbrowse-plugin-msaview">jbrowse-plugin-msaview</a>), so the
      same viewer — alignment, phylogenetic tree, and all — runs as a view <em>inside</em> JBrowse,
      stacked alongside a Linear Genome View with gene annotation and multiple-alignment tracks.
      Every view here is opened by a <strong>declarative link</strong>: the whole multi-view session
      lives in the URL, with nothing to install or set up.
    </p>

    <h2 id="combined-view">A combined view: factor XII lost in whales</h2>
    <p>
      One JBrowse view, two independent panels: the human <strong>F12</strong> locus (coagulation
      factor XII) on hg38 — RefSeq genes and a UCSC Multiz mammal DNA alignment — above the
      react-msaview panel with the F12 coding alignment and its tree. F12 is intact across land
      mammals but <strong>disabled by frameshifts in cetaceans</strong>; the tree groups the
      cetaceans and the shared frameshift is visible in the alignment.
    </p>

    <p>
      <a class="cta" href={links.combined} target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        Open the combined view in JBrowse →
      </a>
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img
        src={`${base}/media/f12-combined-view.png`}
        alt="JBrowse combined view: F12 gene track and Multiz mammal alignment above a react-msaview panel with a phylogenetic tree"
      />
      <figcaption>
        F12 on hg38 — gene track + Multiz 470-way mammal alignment, above the react-msaview panel
        (coding alignment + tree). One declarative URL.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2 id="linked-src">A linked protein view: SRC, beside its gene</h2>
    <p>
      The MSA viewer can also be <strong>connected</strong> to the genome view so the two share
      coordinates. This link opens the human <strong>SRC</strong> proto-oncogene on hg38 beside the
      Src-family kinase alignment, linked through the SRC transcript model so the mapping is a true
      protein-to-nucleotide one:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Click a residue in the alignment → the genome view navigates to that residue's codon.</li>
      <li>Hover the gene in the genome view → the corresponding alignment column highlights.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      <a class="cta" href={links.proteinLinked} target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        Open the linked SRC protein view in JBrowse →
      </a>
    </p>

    <h2 id="braf-v600e">Zoomed on a mutation: BRAF V600E</h2>
    <p>
      The same connected pattern zoomed to a single codon: human <strong>BRAF</strong> beside the
      RAF-family kinase alignment, positioned on the <strong>V600</strong> codon with the matching
      alignment column pre-highlighted. <strong>V600E</strong> (<code>c.1799T&gt;A</code>) is the most
      common oncogenic mutation in melanoma; V600 is <strong>invariant</strong> down the RAF family, so
      the highlighted column is solid, and a <strong>ClinVar pathogenic-variant track</strong> stacks
      disease alleles directly onto the codon.
    </p>

    <p>
      <a class="cta" href={links.brafV600} target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        Open the BRAF V600E view in JBrowse →
      </a>
    </p>

    <h2 id="tp53-r248">Conservation meets pathogenicity: TP53 R248</h2>
    <p>
      A whole clinical archive landing on one conserved column: human <strong>TP53</strong> on hg38
      with a <strong>ClinVar pathogenic-variant track</strong>, beside p53 aligned across thirteen
      vertebrates, positioned on the <strong>R248</strong> codon — the most frequently mutated residue
      in TP53. A dense wall of ClinVar variants stacks on the codon while the alignment column reads
      <code>R</code> in every species: the pathogenic pileup and the conserved column are the same
      position.
    </p>

    <p>
      <a class="cta" href={links.tp53R248} target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        Open the TP53 R248 view in JBrowse →
      </a>
    </p>

    <h2 id="how-built">How the links are built</h2>
    <p>
      Each link is a JBrowse
      <a href="https://jbrowse.org/jb2/docs/urlparams/#session-spec">session spec</a>:
      <code>?config=…&amp;session=spec-&#123;"views":[…]&#125;</code>, where each entry launches a
      <code>LinearGenomeView</code> or an <code>MsaView</code>. To <em>connect</em> the two, the genome
      view gets an <code>id</code> and the <code>MsaView</code> carries a <code>connectedViewId</code>,
      a <code>connectedFeature</code> (the transcript model for the codon mapping), and a
      <code>querySeqName</code> naming the matching alignment row; <code>highlightColumns</code> seeds
      the lit-column overlay. The transcript models and alignment/tree/ClinVar data are regenerated
      reproducibly from public sources by the scripts under <code>scripts/</code>
      (<code>src-protein-link</code>, <code>braf-protein-link</code>, <code>tp53-protein-link</code>). A
      view loaded from a cross-origin config asks you to trust the plugin once before it renders.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
